 by the needs and wishes of those who clung to and depended on them as by the actual figure of the Gaon. In this penetrating study, Immanuel Etkes sheds light on aspects of the Vilna Gaon's "real" character and traces several public images of him as they have developed and spread from the early nineteenth century until the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHasidismxHistoryy18th century. 0aRabbiszLithuaniazVilniusvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aauthority.  abiography.  adisciples.  adivine.  aeastern europe.  aeliahu ben shlomo zalman.  aetkes.  again of vilna.  ajewish authors.  ajewish leaders.  ajewish life.  ajewish.  ajewry.  ajudaica.  ajudaism.  akahal.  amedieval.  anonfiction.  arabbi scholar.  arabbi.  arabbinic studies.  areligion.  areligious belief.  areligious history.  areligious leaders.  areligious men.  atalmud.  atalmudic studies.  atorah.  avilna.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022394340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092507640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520925076423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520925076/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY